During inspection, ham was observed being thawed under running water, which is an approved thawing method, however the water being used was 74F. When thawing under running water, the water temperature should be no more than 70F. During warmer months, be aware of the cold water temperature and pull foods from the freezer with enough time than they can been thawed under refrigeration.

Found one squirt bottle of oil that wasn't labeled. All foods and food ingredients that are not readily and unmistakably recognized, such as dry pasta or beans, must be labeled with common name of food. This is especially important with foods such as cooking oils, flour, herbs, salt, spices, and sugar.
Shut-off observed on hose attached to a hose bib with an atmospheric vacuum breaker with the water left on. These mushroom-shaped backflow preventers located at the faucet of a hose bib are not approved for installation with any shut-offs downstream from preventer when under constant pressure. Remove spray guns, valved splitters, or any other shut offs downstream from backflow preventer and/or make sure to turn water off and relieve pressure when sinks are not in use. If such an attachment is necessary at the hose bib or the water must be left on for extended periods of time, contact a plumber for advice on installing an approved backflow preventer. The water at the sink was turned off and pressure was released during inspection.
When cleaning the can opener, make sure to remove the blade assembly and wash it separately so that all parts are properly cleaned and sanitized.

During inspection, discussed consumer advisory requirements with manager. He stated that customers will very seldom ask for meats to be under cooked but that if it is requested, they serve meat undercooked. Serving any cooked to order meats that are not fully cooked to the final cook temperature for the species of meat requires a consumer advisory which currently is not in place at this facility. Items under consumer advisory must be marked with an asterisk(*), also a disclosure stating that the item(s) marked with * indicate that the item is served cooked to order, raw, or undercooked. A reminder is also required that states that consuming undercooked meat, poultry, seafood, eggs, etc may increase risk of foodborne illness. If this facility chooses to fully cook all meats, a consumer advisory is not required.

Defrosting should occur during slow periods or while the restaurant is closed so that the cooler is not stressed and foods will be maintained at proper temperatures at all times.

Cold holding temperature requirement for potentially hazardous food has changed from 45F to 41F. Points may be deducted for this beginning in 2019. Ready to eat, potentially hazardous foods kept in the establishment more than 24 hours shall be date marked. Date marking should be either a preparation date, or a consume-by date. Establishments may use either a 4 day or 7 day shelf life BASED ON THE ABILITY OF ALL EQUIPMENT IN THE ESTABLISHMENT TO HOLD FOODS AT 41 DEGREES F OR BELOW. Strongly recommend a 4 day shelf life until person in charge can document a track record of all equipment holding foods at 41 F or below. Certain foods, such as cultured milk products, some cheeses, commercially packed deli salads, and some cured or dried meats are exempt from this requirement. Contact your inspector if you have questions about whether a specific item must be date marked. Replace sanitizer test strips which have become wet and no longer test concentration correctly. Reminder: clean, sanitize, and air dry coolers used for direct food contact (tortillas).

Ready to eat, potentially hazardous foods kept in the establishment more than 24 hours past opening or preparation shall be date marked. Date marking should be either a preparation date, or a consume-by date. Establishments may use either a 4 day or 7 day shelf life BASED ON THE ABILITY OF ALL EQUIPMENT IN THE ESTABLISHMENT TO HOLD FOODS AT 41 DEGREES F OR BELOW. Strongly recommend a 4 day shelf life until person in charge can document a track record of all equipment holding foods at 41 F or below. Certain foods, such as cultured milk products, some cheeses, commercially packed deli salads, and some cured or dried meats are exempt from this requirement. Contact your inspector if you have questions about whether a specific item must be date marked.

Reviewed employee health policy during inspection and most of the basic information is correct, however, 1 illnesses listed is not specific enough to comply with NC Food Code requirements. On document available in facility, only E.coli is listed; in order to comply with Food Code, E.coli 0157:H7, Enterohemorrhagic (ETEC) and Shiga toxin-producing (STEC) E. coli must be listed. Additionally, the FDA has added nontyphiodal Salmonella as an illness that is be included in the illness that need to be reported. Policy needs to be updated to include the specific illnesses. The policy also does not include restriction or exclusion time (24-48 hours depending on symptoms/illness), this information should be added to policy so that employees are fully aware how long that have to be out of work if they report foodborne illness symptoms or are diagnosed with a foodborne illness.

*During inspection, quat sanitizer solution was in the 3 compartment sink but was not actively being used however, the solution being dispensed for the sink was only 70F. According to NC Food Code [4-501.114(C)(1)], quat sanitizer solution shall be at least 75F. The dispenser is currently plumbed directly into the cold water line. A mixing valve of some type needs to be installed so that the solution is dispensed at required temperatures or documentation stating that the particular product used in this facility is effective below 75F must be provided.
The 2013 FDA Food Code has added nontyphiodal Salmonella as an illness that is be included in the illness that need to be reported. This is currently not being enforced in NC and is not a violation at this time. This provided for information purposes only, should operator choose to update their existing policy.

If hot dogs or other potentially hazardous foods are opened in the facility and kept for more than 24 hours, they must be date marked. Dish washing procedure for a two compartment sink :
1. Fill one sink basin with soapy water. Wash the dishes.
2. Fill the other sink basin with clean rinse water. Rinse the dishes.
3. Store the dishes on a clean surface while you drain the rinse asin. 
4. Fill the empty basin with sanitizer. Submerge dishes for at least 2 minutes in sanitizer.
5. Air dry dishes.



Hand washing :

Violation Codes
(A) After touching bare human body parts other than clean hands and clean, exposed portions of arms; P 

(B) After using the toilet room; P 

(C) After caring for or handling SERVICE ANIMALS or aquatic animals as specified in ? 2-403.11(B); P

(D) Except as specified in ? 2-401.11(B), after coughing, sneezing, using a handkerchief or disposable tissue, using tobacco, eating, or drinking; P

(E) After handling soiled EQUIPMENT or UTENSILS; P

(F) During FOOD preparation, as often as necessary to remove soil and contamination and to prevent cross contamination when changing tasks; P

(G) When switching between working with raw FOOD and working with READY-TO-EAT FOOD; P

(H) Before donning gloves for working with FOOD; P and

(I) After engaging in other activities that contaminate the hands.P

Individually packaged meals are delivered by Meals on Wheels but these meals are not labeled in any manner and the temperature chart and information sheets that are delivered with the food give no indication of where the food was prepared or packaged. Packaged foods should be labeled as follows: 1) common name of the food 2) list of the food ingredients, if more than 2 ingredients, in descending order 3) accurate declaration of the quantities 4) name and place of business where the food was made, packaged, and/or distributed 5) the name of the food source of each major allergen container in the food unless the source is already in the common name of the food. Additionally, the documentation delivered with the food should have identifying information for the origin of the food.

Food is delivered in pre-portioned single-use trays. The food is delivered by Food Runners. The paperwork delivered with the food identifies what foods are in the trays but does not identify a location where the food is prepared. The source of the food needs to be included in the paper work if each tray is not labeled individually.

Consumption of Animal Foods that are Raw, Undercooked, or Not Otherwise Processed to Eliminate Pathogens - Establishment found to offer at least one undercooked animal-based food and has insufficient consumer advisory. Consumer advisory shall be provided for any undercooked animal-based food with the exception of some steaks. Consumer advisory must consist of a disclosure, wherein the name of the food on the menu indicates that it may be served undercooked, such as "Hamburger (cooked to order)," and the disclosure must be asterisked to a reminder stating the following: "Consuming raw or undercooked meats, poultry, seafood, shellfish, or eggs may increase your risk of foodborne illness." (Two alternate statements are available; ask your inspector if you have questions.) Please contact your inspector with any questions about this rule, or to have proposed wording approved before modifying menu. No violation observed.

In the special needs class bathrooms, alcohol based Sani-Hands wipes are provided for wiping down diaper changing areas. While this is not a direct violation of NC School Sanitation Rules, these wipes are meant for sanitizing hands, not cleaning or disinfecting diaper changing surfaces. Because the children using these facilities may have weakened or compromised immune systems, it is highly recommended to use a hospital grade disinfectant and use proper clean up after diaper changing procedures. Proper procedure entails wiping the surface down with a soapy water solution then follow with a disinfectant solution. Disinfecting wipes, meant for use on hard surfaces, would be a safe alternative to disinfecting sprays.

EDUCATIONAL NOTE ABOUT PROPER DATE MARKING:  Ready to eat, potentially hazardous foods (PHF) kept in the establishment more than 24 hours shall be date marked. This includes canned PHF put in different containers, on-site prepared potentially hazardous salads, opened deli meat packages, cartons of milk, etc.  Date marking should be either a preparation date or a consume-by date.  Establishments may use either a 7 day shelf life BASED ON THE ABILITY OF ALL EQUIPMENT IN THE ESTABLISHMENT TO HOLD FOODS AT 41 DEGREES F OR BELOW or a 4 day shelf life if equipment can only hold foods between 41F and 45F.  Strongly recommend a 4 day shelf life until person in charge can document a track record of all equipment holding foods at 41 degrees F or below.   Certain foods, such as cultured milk products, some cheeses, commercially packed deli salads, and some cured or dried meats are exempt from this requirement.   Contact your inspector if you have questions about whether a specific food must be date marked.

Employee health policy was available for review at time of inspection. There were some aspects of the policy that are not compliance with NC Food Code requirements. Taco Bell policy mentions exposure for pre-employment but not after employment. All food handling employees must be made aware that the are required to report exposures to illnesses listed in policy. Exposure may include but is not limited to caring for a sick family member or roommate and/or spending time in close proximity with some that has been diagnosed with a foodborne illness. Taco Bell policy also mentions Salmonella but states "All Types". Food Code requires that policy specifically states Salmonella typhi/typhoid fever. If policy is updated, recommend adding non-typhoidal Salmonella as well to be in compliance with 2013 FDA Food Code. 2013 FDA Food Code is not effective in NC at this time. Contact inspector with questions about employee health policy.

The 2013 FDA Food Code has added non-typhoidal salmonella to the list of reportable illnesses, however this is not currently being enforced in NC. This statement is for informational purposes only, should corporate wish to update policy to comply with current national standard.

Items such as as eggs and or meats may be cooked less than the required minimum cook temperature for safe food, if the customer orders the food that way and you provide a proper consumer advisory.   A proper consumer advisory includes a disclosure such as "This item may be cooked to order" and a reminder such as "Consuming raw or undercooked meats , poultry, seafood, shellfish, or eggs may increase your risk of foodborne illness, especially if you have certain medical conditions.  This would be located with the food item or in a footnote by asterisking (*) the food item and putting a footnote preceded by another asterisks(*).

Please note that hermetically sealed foods purchased from a farm are not necessarily approved for use in a food establishment. Foods in hermetically sealed containers, such as jarred or canned foods, are approved ONLY if they are "obtained from a FOOD PROCESSING PLANT that is regulated by the FOOD regulatory agency that has jurisdiction over the plant." If the farm cannot demonstrate that their canning process is regulated by the Department of Agriculture, their hermetically sealed products should not be brought into the establishment.  Jars were removed to office as a precaution so that they would not be used.

At the 3 compartment sink, the quat sanitizer solution dispenser is plumbed directly into the hot water line below the sink and is being dispensed at 130F. This is not a direct violation of NC Food Code but high temperatures can cause the testing strips, that are used to check the concentration, to react incorrectly and cause a false high sanitizer concentration reading. Quat sanitizer should be at around 75-110F for proper testing. It is recommended to either install a mixing valve at the water line so that the temperature is regulated or have a valve installed on the faucet that will allow for the temperature to be manually adjusted.

3-603.11 Consumption of Animal Foods that are Raw, Undercooked, or Not Otherwise Processed to Eliminate Pathogens - Establishment found to offer at least one undercooked animal-based food and has insufficient consumer advisory. Consumer advisory shall be provided for any undercooked animal-based food with the exception of some steaks. Consumer advisory must consist of a disclosure, wherein the name of the food on the menu indicates that it may be served undercooked, such as “Hamburger (cooked to order),” and the disclosure must be asterisked to a reminder stating the following: “Consuming raw or undercooked meats, poultry, seafood, shellfish, or eggs may increase your risk of foodborne illness.” (Two alternate statements are available; ask your inspector if you have questions.) Please contact your inspector with any questions about this rule, or to have proposed wording approved before modifying menu.

The employee health acknowledgment form included in the employee training packet meets employee health policy requirements but the supplemental signs posted in the department is missing a few items. The poster does not include an infected wound on the hands or arms and the illnesses listed are not specific enough, the illness are listed as E.coli, Salmonella, Shigella, Hepatitis, and Norovirus. The following illnesses need to specifically listed: E.coli 0157:H7, Enterotoxigenic (ETEC) and Shiga toxin-producing (STEC) and Salmonella typhi; additionally, the FDA has added nontyphoidal Salmonella to illness that must be reported to management for exclusion or restriction from food handling/prep.

Facility receives pizza delivered from Domino's, which Iceplex employees distribute to birthday party clients along with cake and ice cream. No snack bar food present at time of inspection to check hot or cold holding temperatures (only in freezer). Employees may not touch any ready-to-eat foods with bare hands. Employees shall use gloves, utensils, deli papers, etc. in lieu of bare-hand contact. As a reminder, employees shall wash their hands before putting on gloves and at any glove change. Gloves shall be changed when switching between raw and cooked foods, after cleaning activities, after touching hair or face, and after any other activities that may soil gloves. Ready to eat, potentially hazardous foods kept in the establishment more than 24 hours past opening or preparation shall be date marked. Date marking should be either a preparation date, or a consume-by date. Establishments may use either a 4 day or 7 day shelf life BASED ON THE ABILITY OF ALL EQUIPMENT IN THE ESTABLISHMENT TO HOLD FOODS AT 41 DEGREES F OR BELOW. Strongly recommend a 4 day shelf life until person in charge can document a track record of all equipment holding foods at 41 F or below. Certain foods, such as cultured milk products, some cheeses, commercially packed deli salads, and some cured or dried meats are exempt from this requirement. Contact your inspector if you have questions about whether a specific item must be date marked. Replace missing ceiling tiles in janitor's closet.

Correct cooling is achieved rapidly, from 135-70F within two hours and 70-45F within a total of six hours. Use rapid cooling methods such as: "(1) Placing the FOOD in shallow pans; Pf
(2) Separating the FOOD into smaller or thinner portions; Pf
(3) Using rapid cooling EQUIPMENT; Pf
(4) Stirring the FOOD in a container placed in an ice water bath; Pf
(5) Using containers that facilitate heat transfer; Pf
(6) Adding ice as an ingredient; Pf or
(7) Other effective methods. Pf  
(B) When placed in cooling or cold holding EQUIPMENT, FOOD containers in which FOOD is being cooled shall be:  
1) Arranged in the EQUIPMENT to provide maximum heat transfer through the container walls; and
(2) Loosely covered, or uncovered if protected from overhead contamination as specified under Subparagraph 3 305.11(A)(2), during the cooling period to facilitate heat transfer from the surface of the FOOD. "

ISSUES REGARDING TIME AS PUBLIC HEALTH CONTROL:  If time as a public health control will be used for certain potentially hazardous foods, a time control sheet (previously given to manager) must be completed for each food and food must be properly labeled according to the sheet. Foods CANNOT be on time control and temperature control at the same time. Once a food is on time control, it must stay on time control. If it is on temperature control, it must stay on temperature control. If on time control, food can only be on display for a maximum of 4 hours and then thrown away at the end of the 4 hour period. Keep records of foods on time control in the restaurant at all times for review by the health department upon request.

1. The initial cooking step must be less than 60 minutes.

4. The chicken is reheated to 165 F for at least 15 seconds. 
5. You have written procedures for this process.

During inspection, dishes were being cleaned and sanitized in the dish machine but the 3 compartment sink was being set up and the quat sanitizing solution was being dispensed at 53F. NC Food Code requires a minimum temperature of 75F for quat sanitizers. At 53F the solution was registering around 400 ppm and PIC stated that they usually dilute the solution using hot water to bring the temperature up to 75F and lower the concentration to around 200 ppm. As long as the solution is being used at the correct minimum temperature and the concentration meets minimum requirements, methods used by this facility are allowed but it is recommended to have a mixing valve installed so that the solution temperature is regulated at 75-110F and hot water does not have to be added manually to dilute the sanitizing solutions.
At the automatic handsink next to the dish area, the water temperature cannot be manually adjusted and was reaching 130F. This temperature can cause scalding and does not allow for proper handwashing. The water temperature needs to be adjusted so that it is at least 100F but does not exceed 120F. Ideal handwashing temperature is 110-115F.

At start of inspection, the water from the automatic mixing faucet on the handsink by the dish pit was 126F. This is too hot to properly handwash. The mixing valve below the sink was adjusted during inspection and the temperature was brought down to 106F. Hot water at handsinks must be at least 100F but should not exceed 120F.

BECAUSE OF THE PROXIMATY OF THE HANDSINK TO THE 2 COMPARTMENT DISH SINK, THE RIGHT BASIN OF THE SINK SHOULD BE DESIGNATED AS THE "DIRTY" BASIN, ONLY DISHES BEING CLEANED OR WAITING TO BE CLEANED SHOULD BE IN THIS AREA.  THE LEFT BASIN SHOULD BE DESIGNATED AS THE "CLEAN" BASIN AND SHOULD ONLY BE USED FOR SANITIZING CLEAN UTENSILS AND EQUIPMENT.  CLEAN UTENSILS MAY NOT BE AIR DRIED OR STORED ON THE COUNTER IN THE AREA BETWEEN THE HANDSINK AND THE DISH SINK.  CLEAN ITEMS SHOULD BE AIR DRIED AFTER WASHING AND SANITIZING ON A CLEAN COUNTER OR CART IN AN AREA WHERE THEY ARE PROTECTED FROM CONTAMINATION.  IF THE 2 COMPARMENT SINK IS ENEDED FOR FOOD PREPARATION, SUCH AS THAWING FROZEN FOODS, A SPLASHGUARD MUST BE INSTALLED BETWEEN THE 2 COMPARTMENT SINK AND THE HANDSINK.  ALSO, THE 2 COMPARTMENT SINK MUST BE THOROUGHLY CLEANED AND SANITIZED BETWEEN USE FOR DIS WASHING AND USE FOR FOOD PREPARATION.

Lamb Gyro Procedures

Definition: Gyro is a cone of seasoned restructured, ground raw meat.
?	All meat are obtained and inspected from approved source.
?	Meat cone comes in frozen. Must be kept frozen until ready to be cooked.

Cooking Instructions: 
?	Remove frozen meat cone from the freezer, mount on Skewer pit and place directly on the rotating vertical broiler.
?	Once the exterior of the meat cone is cooked, (use thermometer probe temperature should reach 165°) using a clean, sanitized knife, slice approximately    ¼ inch thick slices.  Meat must be cooked completely before storing in the warmer; it may need to be cooked on the grill so that the inside surface also reaches 165°
?	Sliced cooked meat then held in a (warmer) heat unit at 145° until ready to serve.

During busy lunch or special events
?	Gyro meat is sliced off the cone (according to instruction above).  After all parts reach at least 165° temperature including being cooked on the grill, cut to small pieces, then held in a warmer at 145°, ready to serve.
?	Gyro cone will be continuously cooked no more than 2-3 hours.
?	Fully Cooked Gyros Slices may be cooled in a shallow metal pan, spread out  (only 2 inches high), then cooled uncovered in a refrigerator to below 45°.  After the cooling process it can be covered & stacked (or combined).

Establishment has proposed using AUTODONER Vertical Broilers for cooking chicken.  This procedure has been researched and may be done with the following guidance:  
1)  This piece of equipment is approved to cook any type of meat, but amount of meat must be limited such that it does not remain on the broiler for more than 6 hours. (However, see additional limitations in 3-401.14 .)
2)As this cooking method, as described, does not fully cook each chicken breast to 165 degrees F for 15 seconds, portions of chicken that are not immediately moved to grill to cook to 165 degrees F are considered to be part of a non-continuous cooking process.
3) Non-continuous cooking processes are subject to the rules set forth in 3-401.14 (copy provided during inspection)
4) Establishment must either move all chicken to the grill to fully cook it to 165 degrees F immediately after cutting from broiler OR develop procedures and documentation and submit to Wake County Environmental Services for approval as required by the Rules.  
5) Please provide these procedures and documentation within 30 days.

Nail brushes are being hung from the handsink faucets in the kitchen. While nail brushes can improve removal of soil from hands, they should be stored so that they are being contaminated while hands are being washed and so that they can air dry. The brushes should be cleaned and sanitized at least every 4 hours throughout the work day to prevent growth of harmful bacteria.

The dining room wait station has a handsink but it is labeled as a dump sink. This sink is required to be a handsink due to distance from another convenient handsink and staff is scooping ice at this station. Remove the dump sink sign and set up as a handsink. Do not dump beverages in this sink.
Nail brushes are hung on the handsink faucets in the front prep/service areas, this poses a contamination risk to the brushes that are intended to be used to remove soil from under the nails. To prevent potential cross-contamination, the nail brushes should be stored in a manner that will protect them from splash contamination during handwashing and allow them to dry between uses, also the brushes should be cleaned and sanitized frequently throughout the day. If the brushes are not required by company policy, it is recommended to remove them all together. Follow-Up: 04/27/2015

During inspection, date marking of potato salad was discussed. Current Smithfield's policy, according to manager, is to date the potato salad with the date that it is assembled but the potatoes used for the potato salad are frequently cooked and cooled a day prior to when the potato salad is actually assembled. NC Food Code date marking requirements are to date marked potentially hazardous food items with the date that the oldest ingredient used in the food product was prepared or opened. The refrigeration in this facility holds food well below 40F so by NC Food Code requirements, foods may be held up to 7 days but the correct date must be used. According to manager, Smithfield's policy is that potato salad must be used or discarded within 4 days of potato salad assembly date. Contact inspector with any questions regarding date marking requirements.

Properly mixed sanitizer (quaternary ammonia or bleach and water) must be made available during operation times.  Quat sanitizer must be 200-400 ppm.  Bleach and water sanitizer must be 50-200 ppm.  Use test strips to check sanitizer concentrations.  If hot dogs or other potentially hazardous foods are opened in the facility and kept for more than 24 hours, they must be date marked.  Date marking should be either a preparation date, or a consume-by/discard date.  If foods are maintained at 41°F or below they may be held up to 7 days; if holding between 42°F and 45°F, foods may only be held up to 4 days.  Certain foods are exempt from this requirement.  Contact your inspector if you have questions about whether a specific item must be date marked.

Because of the proximity of the hand sink to the 2 compartment dish sink, the right basin of the sink should be designated as the "dirty" basin, only dishes being cleaned or waiting to be cleaned should be in this area. The left basin should be designated as the "clean" basin and should only be sued for sanitizing clean utensils and equipment. Clean utensils may not be air dried or stored on the counter in the area between the hand sink and the dish sink. Clean items should be air dried after washing and sanitizing on a clean counter or cart in an area where they are protected from contamination. If the 2 compartment sink is needed for food preparation, such as thawing frozen foods, a splashguard must be installed between the 2 compartment sink and the hand sink. Also, the 2 compartment sink must be thoroughly cleaned and sanitized between use for dish washing and use for food preparation.

Facility has started cooking and cooling spaghetti noodles. The noodles are cooked, cooled under running cold water, then bagged and frozen. Recommend adding ice while rinsing the noodles in cold water and leaving the bags open after portioning to allow any residual heat to escape. Also, remember to date mark the noodles on the date that they are prepared then the date they are pulled from the freezer to thaw. The preparation date is Day 1, the pull/thaw date is Day 2. If the noodles are maintained at 41F or less, they can be held for up to 7 days. If held between 41F and 45F, the noodles can only be held for 4 days.

Establishment has steaks on menu.  Menu does not speak to cooking to order and PIC states that they serve all steaks fully cooked.  Please be aware that animal products such as steaks can be cooked to a less than fully cooked state if a consumer advisory is provided.  Consumer advisory must consist of a disclosure, wherein the name of the food on the menu indicates that it may be served undercooked, such as "Hamburger (cooked to order)," and the disclosure must be asterisked to a reminder stating the following: "Consuming raw or undercooked meats, poultry, seafood, shellfish, or eggs may increase your risk of foodborne illness." (Two alternate statements are available, ask your inspector if you have questions.) Please contact your inspector with any questions about this rule, or to have proposed wording if establishment elects to cook steaks to order.

We discussed COOLING of chicken today.  Hot chicken going into the freezer has caused some problems. It is acceptable to have chicken briefly stored at room temperature. We looked at handouts and discussed that cooling effectiveness is measured by food temperature. Chicken temperature starts around 200 degrees. From the time any part of the food reaches 135F, it shall be 70F or colder in less than 2 hours.  Chicken should be spread out into shallow layers on metal pans, spaced on speed rack, uncovered or loosely covered. Use your thermometer.

Ready to eat, potentially hazardous foods kept in the establishment more than 24 hours shall be date marked. Date marking should be either a preparation date, or a consume-by date. Establishments may use either a 4 day or 7 day shelf life BASED ON THE ABILITY OF ALL EQUIPMENT IN THE ESTABLISHMENT TO HOLD FOODS AT 41 DEGREES F OR BELOW. Strongly recommend a 4 day shelf life until you document a track record of all equipment holding foods at 41 F or below. Certain foods, such as cultured milk products, some cheeses, commercially packed deli salads, and some cured or dried meats are exempt from this requirement. Ricotta Cheese and soft mozzarella should be dated if opened for more than 24 hours.  .  .  .  .  .  .

Your Quaternary Ammonia Compound (QAC)sanitizer has an effective range of 150-400 parts per million (ppm). It comes out of the dispenser at 150 ppm. It is in the range but since sanitizer tends to get weaker not stronger over time, it will get too weak very quickly. The dispenser  should mix it so it comes out in the middle of the range or near the top of the range so when it weakens, the sanitizer will still be in the range.

Discussed cooling of chicken and chicken broth during inspection. Chicken broth was being cooled by placing a large bucket type container on the prep sink drainboard with an ice wand, it appeared to be reaching required cooling parameters but it is recommended to either cool the broth using the ice wand in an ice bath or in the freezer. The chicken was pulled off the bone and chopped after cooking, which brought the temperature down significantly and was then put into a pan about 6 inches deep and placed in the freezer, however, the thickness of the chicken in the container could impede the cooling process. Recommend spreading the chicken out on a sheet pan or separating it out into 2 containers to lessen the thickness of the food. 

Also discussed labeling on portioned chicken salad for sale as a "grab and go" item. Foods that are available for customer self-service must be properly labeled as follows: 1) common name of the food 2) list of the food ingredients, if more than 2 ingredients, in descending order 3) accurate declaration of the quantities 4) name and place of business where the food was made, packaged, and/or distributed 5) the name of the food source of each major allergen container in the food unless the source is already in the common name of the food; they were not being used during inspection, but the Red Bull and Pepsi coolers in the dining room are not approved for foods that are packaged in the restaurant. The Red Bull cooler is not an approved piece of equipment. The Pepsi cooler is NSF approved but only for packaged or bottled products that are in the original, sealed container.

Store student clothing in cubicles so that different individual's personal clothing items do not touch.

At the 3 compartment sink, the quat sanitizer dispenser is plumbed into the hot water line and sanitizer solution is dispensed at greater than 120F. This is not a violation according to the NC Food Code but the high temperature could cause the quat test strips to inaccurately measure the chemical concentration due to a reaction to the heat. the sign posted at the sink, by the chemical supplier, states that the solution should be measured when it is between 65F and 75F; NC Food Code specifies a minimum of 75F unless manufacturer specifications state otherwise. A mixing valve may need to be installed to bring the water temperature down.

At start of inspection, opened sanitizer packets were observed floating in the sanitizer solution that was used to sanitize breakfast dishes, there was still some sanitizer concentrate residue in the packets. During inspection, a final cook temperature was taken on catfish fillets. These are a new product and some pieces are thicker than others. When the cook was taking the temperature on the fish, EHS observed only a few pieces being checked, these pieces were thinner than others. The temperature was exceeding 165F on the thin pieces, however, EHS checked some thicker pieces and found the temperature only reaching 112 degrees on some pieces. The fish was put back into the oven to continue cooking. EHS advised cafeteria staff to be sure and check thicker pieces of fish, in addition to the thinner pieces to insure proper cooking. The labeling on the catfish is unclear as to whether or not the fish is fully cooked, it only says oven-ready and give instructions to cook the fish to at least 145F, which is just above the 140F final cook temperature for seafood. CNS standard requires 165F as a cook temperature for almost all foods.

Facility cooks raw chicken and raw beef shawarma cones. Cooked/partially cooked meat is shaved off the cone and finished on the flat top grill then immediately served or held hot. This practice is very good, however, any meat that is left on the cones at the end of the night must be shaved off, cooked, then cooked if the meat is to be saved and used the following day. Partially cooked/heated cones may not be cooled and reheated.

PLEASE NOTE:  Establishment observed in the process of making paneer.   As described, this process will probably not require a variance as long as the following conditions are met:  1) The addition of vinegar is done while the product is hot and the resulting product is rapidly cooled by approved methods within 6 hours (135 F to 70F within the first two hours); 2) The resulting product is treated as potentially hazardous, held at 45/41 F or below, properly date marked, and discarded at the end of 4/7 days (depending on restaurant cold holding temperatures); 3) Product is prepared with approved food service equipment and utensils.  To ensure that this process meets requirements, please submit recipe/procedure AND temperature logs for the next three batches.  Please include time and temperature for the time the vinegar was added, when separation was completed, and hourly during the cooling process.  Please email this information to James Smith at jamesrsmith@wakegov.com . If it is found that this process will require a variance or HACCP plan, additional guidance will be provided.

Sanitation Grade card missing from Delivery window.  Sanitation grade card in dining area was covered by coffee mugs.  Sanitation grade Cards shall be visible to the public at all times.  Management shall be responsible for maintaining the sanitation grade card in such a  manner that the Grade Card is visible at all times and is maintained at the location where the Environmental Health Specialist posted the card. Failure to maintain the grade card could result in possible legal action. 
15A NCAC 18A .2660 PUBLIC DISPLAY OF GRADE CARDS
(a) Upon initial inspection of a food establishment or if a renovation or other change in the establishment makes the grade card inconspicuous, the regulatory authority shall designate the location for posting the grade card. The grade card shall be located in a conspicuous place where it may be readily observed by the public upon entering the food establishment. If the person in charge of the food establishment objects to the location designated by the regulatory authority then the person in charge may suggest an alternative location which meets the criteria of this Rule.
(b) When an inspection of a food establishment is made, the regulatory authority shall remove the existing grade card, issue a new grade card, and post the new grade card in the same location where the grade card was previously posted as long as that location remains conspicuous. The person in charge of the food establishment shall keep the grade card posted at the designated location at all times. The grade card may be posted in another location which meets the criteria of this Rule if agreed upon by the person in charge and the regulatory authority.

When doing Time as a public health : (A) Except as specified under ¶ (D) of this section, if time without temperature control is used as the public health control for a working supply of POTENTIALLY HAZARDOUS FOOD (TIME/TEMPERATURE CONTROL FOR SAFETY FOOD) before cooking, or for READY-TO-EAT POTENTIALLY HAZARDOUS FOOD (TIME/TEMPERATURE CONTROL FOR SAFETY FOOD) that is displayed or held for sale or service: 
(1) Written procedures shall be prepared in advance, maintained in the FOOD ESTABLISHMENT and made available to the REGULATORY AUTHORITY upon request that specify: Pf
(a) Methods of compliance with Subparagraphs (B)(1)-(3) or C)(1)-(5) of this section; Pf and
(b) Methods of compliance with § 3-501.14 for FOOD that is prepared, cooked, and refrigerated before time is used as a public health control. Pf"

(B) If time without temperature control is used as the public health control up to a maximum of 4 hours: 
(1) The FOOD shall have an initial temperature of 5°C (41°F) or less, or 7°C (45°F) or less when removed from cold holding temperature control, or 57°C (135°F) or greater when removed from hot holding temperature control; P
(2) The FOOD shall be marked or otherwise identified to indicate the time that is 4 hours past the point in time when the FOOD is removed from temperature control; Pf 
(3) The FOOD shall be cooked and served, served at any temperature if READY-TO-EAT, or discarded, within 4 hours from the point in time when the FOOD is removed from temperature control; P and
(4) The FOOD in unmarked containers or PACKAGES, or marked to exceed a 4-hour limit shall be discarded.

During inspection, observed good hand washing and good use of no bare hand contact with ready to eat foods. However, employees on the cooking line were observed wearing gloves while using utensils to cook and handle other foods when not needed. Gloves are not required to be worn if foods can be handled with tongs, spoons, or other utensils. When gloves are not worn properly, it can actually increase risk of cross-contamination. Gloves are only required to be used when ready to eat food is handled without a utensil or other barrier. Recommend using different colored gloves if wearing gloves for handling and preparing raw meat.
